<h1>5.2 Order of subject and verb</h1>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes-syntactic-relation-labels">Relevant postag
codes / syntactic relation labels</h2>
<p><strong>Syntactic label:</strong> The subject is annotated as SBJ and
the main predicate of the sentence receives the label PRED. If the verb
is in a subordinate clause, its relation reflects its function to its
linguistic parent.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li>ὁ παρʼ ἐμὲ ἐκλήμπτωρ ἐπʼ ἐμβάσει ἐστίν·<br>
ho par’ emè eklḗmptōr ep’ embásei estín.<br>
<em>My contractor is on (our) doorstep.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1085">bgu.16.2663</a>, 5, sent. 4,
transl. Brashear (2015)</li>
</ol>
<p></p><div style="height:300px; " data-treeid="1" class="sentence-tree tf-tree tf-result" data-json=""></div><p></p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>The most common ordering is <em>subject-verb</em>.</p>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<p>In Ancient Greek, the subject is often omitted in sentences where it
can be understood from the the personal ending of the verb and the
context, e.g.&nbsp;if the subject has already been mentioned in a previous
sentence and is not changed <span class="citation" data-cites="emde2019">(<strong>emde2019?</strong>)</span>.</p>
<p>In the literary treebanked corpus, the number of sentences in which
the subject is explicitly mentioned is higher than the number of
sentences where it has been omitted (60% vs.&nbsp;40%). In the PapyGreek
corpus, there is a significant variation between the different genres -
private letters and petitions have far fewer sentences with explicitly
mentioned SBJ - only 20% of all sentences, while legal and
administration documents have a nearly equal split between sentences
with overt subject and sentences where the subject has been omitted.
This tendency can be observed also in the Duke-nlp corpus (!!Ref
needed).</p>
<p>There is an obvious difference between the genres also in the
dominant order patterns. In private correspondence and petitions, when
the subject is the only obligatory verbal complement present in the
sentence, it is nearly twice as common for it to be placed before than
after the verb:</p>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li><strong>Τύχων</strong> <strong>ἥκει</strong> εἰς τὴν πόλιν τούτου
χάριν·<br>
Túchōn hḗkei eis tḕn pólin toútu chárin.<br>
<em>Tychon is coming to the city because of this.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1068">bgu.16.2646</a>, 38-39, sent.
18.</li>
</ol>
<p>As the subject is often the topic of the sentence, its position
before the verb is in line with the information structure suggested by
the pragmatic paradigm <span class="citation" data-cites="dik1995">(Dik
1995)</span>.</p>
<p>In legal documents, however, the ratio between <em>subject-verb</em>
and <em>verb-subject</em> instances is nearly equal, due to the large
numbers of verb-initial legal formulae:</p>
<ol start="3" type="1">
<li><p><strong>[ὁμ]ολογῖ Αὐρήλιος [Διο]σκοράμμ̣ω̣ν̣
[Σα]ρ̣απίωνος</strong>.<br>
homologeî Aurḗlios Dioskorámmōn Sarapíōnos.<br>
<em>Aurelius Dioskorammon, son of Sarapion, acknowledges.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/39830">p.sakaon.61</a>, 1-3, sent.
8.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>ἔγραψεν</strong> ὑπὲρ τοῦ Ψεμμίνιος <strong>Διονύ̣σ̣ιος
[Ἀ]ρχεδήμου Βερενικεὺς</strong> [ἀ]ξιωθεὶς ὑπʼ αὐτοῦ διὰ τὸ μ̣ὴ εἰδέναι
γράμματα.<br>
égrapsen hupèr toû Psemmínios Dionúsios Archedḗmou Berenikeùs axiōtheìs
hyp’ autoû dià tò mḕ eidénai grámmata.<br>
<em>I, Dionysios, son of Archedemos, from Berenice, wrote for Pseminnis
with his approval, because he does not know the letters.</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/21506">p.adl.G4</a>, 20-25, sent.
5.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>[ἐμαρ]τυροποιήσατο ἡ Βαβαθα</strong> ὡς προγέγραπται διὰ
ἐπιτρόπου αὐτῆς τοῦδε τοῦ πράγματ[ος] [Ἰούδου] [Χ]θουσίωνος ὃς παρὼν
ὑπέγραψεν.<br>
emarturopoiḗsato hē Babatha hōs progégraptai dià epitrópou autês toûde
toû prágmatos Ioúdou Chthousiōnos hòs parṑn hupégrapsen.<br>
<em>Babatha deposed as aforestated through her guardian for this matter,
Judah son of Khthousion, who was present and subscribed.</em> <a href="https://papygreek.com/text/22323">p.babatha.15</a>, 33-34, sent.
9, transl. Lewis (1989)</p></li>
</ol>
<p>The part of speach of the subject also appears to play a role in its
placement with respect to the verb. In the literary corpus, pronoun
subjects have a higher ratio of pre-verbal to post-verbal instances than
noun subjects. This tendency can be traced in PapyGreek’s corpus, but is
not present in the automatically annotated <a href="https://github.com/alekkeersmaekers/duke-nlp/tree/master/xml">Duke-nlp
corpus of documentary papyri</a>.</p>
